quran[23]{c,v,t,f}:
  88,25,"Indeed, to Us is their return."
  88,26,"Then indeed, upon Us is their account."
  89,22,"And your Lord has come{1} and the angels, rank upon rank,",footnotes:1:To pass judgement. See footnote to 2:19
  89,23,"And brought [within view], that Day, is Hell - that Day, man will remember, but how [i.e., what good] to him will be the remembrance?"
  89,24,"He will say, ",footnotes:1:The everlasting life of the Hereafter.
  90,16,"Or a needy person in misery"
  90,17,"And then being among those who believed and advised one another to patience and advised one another to compassion."
  90,18,"Those are the companions of the right.{1}",footnotes:1:Or "the companions of good fortune," i.e., those who receive their records in their right hands and proceed to Paradise.
  91,13,"And the messenger of Allāh [i.e., Ṣāliḥ] said to them, "
  91,14,"But they denied him and hamstrung{1} her. So their Lord brought down upon them destruction for their sin and made it equal [upon all of them].",footnotes:1:And then killed.
  91,15,"And He does not fear the consequence thereof.{1}",footnotes:1:Allāh is not asked about what He does, but His servants will be asked. See 21:23
  92,10,"We will ease him toward difficulty."
  92,11,"And what will his wealth avail him when he falls?{1}",footnotes:1:i.e., when he dies or is destroyed. It can also mean when he falls into the Hellfire.
  92,12,"Indeed, [incumbent] upon Us is guidance."
  93,7,"And He found you lost and guided [you],"
  93,8,"And He found you poor and made [you] self-sufficient."
  93,9,"So as for the orphan, do not oppress [him]."
  94,4,"And raised high for you your repute."
  94,5,"For indeed, with hardship [will be] ease [i.e., relief]."
  94,6,"Indeed, with hardship [will be] ease."
  95,1,"By the fig and the olive{1}",footnotes:1:Referring to the places known for their production, i.e., Damascus and Jerusalem, respectively. It could also refer to the fig and olive trees or to the fruits themselves.
  95,2,"And [by] Mount Sinai"
  95,3,"And [by] this secure city [i.e., Makkah],"